TY  - JOUR
AU  - Faulkender, Michael
AU  - Petersen, Mitchell
T1  - Investment and Capital Constraints: Repatriations Under the American Jobs Creation Act
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhs092
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 11
SP  - 3351
EP  - 3388
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The American Jobs Creation Act (AJCA) significantly lowered U.S. firms' tax cost when accessing their unrepatriated foreign earnings. Using this temporary shock to the cost of internal financing, we examine the role of capital constraints in firms' investment decisions. Controlling for the capacity to repatriate foreign earnings under the AJCA, we find that a majority of the funds repatriated by capital-constrained firms were allocated to approved domestic investment. Although unconstrained firms account for a majority of repatriated funds, no increase in investment resulted. Contrary to other examinations of the AJCA, we find little change in leverage and equity payouts.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhs092
ER  - 



