TY  - JOUR
AU  - Longstaff, Francis A.
AU  - Wang, Jiang
T1  - Asset Pricing and the Credit Market
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhs086
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 11
SP  - 3169
EP  - 3215
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This article studies the central role of the credit market. We show that the credit market facilitates optimal risk sharing by allowing less risk-averse investors to take on levered positions and consume more risk. The equilibrium amount behaves procyclically when aggregate consumption is low but countercyclically when it is high. The varying size of the credit market modifies the amount of risk sharing, which in turn influences asset prices such as expected stock returns, stock return volatility, and the term structure of interest rates. Our article provides a frictionless benchmark for the role and the behavior of the credit market.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhs086
ER  - 



